04284nam a22006135i 9780774838306DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2017279074  a97807748383067 a10.59962/97807748383062doi  a(DE-B1597)661396  a(OCoLC)1049974769  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aF1035.M87bS45 2018 7aSOC0390002bisacsh04a305.6/9709712231 aSelby, Jennifer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond Accommodation :bEveryday Narratives of Muslim Canadians /cLori G. Beaman, Jennifer Selby, Amelie Barras. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (284 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tFigures That Haunt the Everyday -- tKnowledge Production and Muslim Canadians’ Historical Trajectories -- tSecularism in Canada -- tNarratives of Navigation and Negotiation -- tMutual Respect and Working Out Difference -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aProblems – of integration, failed political participation, and requests for various kinds of accommodation – seem to dominate the research on minority Muslims in Western nations. Beyond Accommodation offers a different perspective, showing how Muslim Canadians successfully navigate and negotiate their religiosity in the more mundane moments of their lives. Drawing on interviews with Muslims in Montreal and St. John’s, Selby, Barras, and Beaman examine moments in which religiosity is worked out. They critique the model of reasonable accommodation, which has been lauded internationally for acknowledging and accommodating religious and cultural differences. The authors suggest that it disempowers religious minorities by implicitly privileging Christianity and by placing the onus on minorities to make requests for accommodation. The interviewees show that informal negotiation occurs all the time; scholars, however, have not been paying attention. This book advances a new model for studying the navigation and negotiation of religion in the public sphere and presents an alternative picture of how religious difference is woven into the fabric of Canadian society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslamxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aMuslimsxReligious lifezCanada. 0aMuslimszCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aReligious minoritieszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh1 aBarras, Amelie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBeaman, Lori G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311141792940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483830640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774838306423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774838306/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-141792-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles